    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe behavior of `vim.fn.getchar()` (and `vim.fn.getcharstr()`) is not consistent when it comes to throwing an error for pressing `<C-c>` during execution as a Lua function.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean`\n2. `:lua x = vim.fn.getchar()` and press `<C-c>`. This throws a `E5108: Lua: Keyboard interrupt` error.\n3. `:nnoremap <C-c> <C-c>` and try previous step again. It results in no error and `:=x` shows `3`.\n\nAttempting the same in Vimscript (both in Neovim and Vim) via `:let x = getchar()` has similar but slightly different behavior: no error in the first case (`:echo g:x` shows `E121: Undefined variable`) and the same behavior in the second. So not sure if this is a Vim only issue.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe behavior of `getchar()` does not depend on user mappings.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-484+g492b8c9e9c\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nYes and no\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 7.0.5-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage",
    "closed_at": null,
